SECTION 1: THE QUICK RULES (EVERYTHING IN ONE PLACE)


THE CORE PRINCIPLE
If a player knows the recipe and has the ingredients, the brew always works.
There is no pass/fail roll for whether a potion is produced.
The Guile roll only determines if the potion is better than Standard.


STEP-BY-STEP ADJUDICATION

Step 1 — Establish What the Player Knows
  Alchemy has no ingredient cap. Anyone can combine any number of ingredients.
  The only question is: does the player know the Essences of each ingredient?

  Knowledge is obtained through:
    Rawcraft:     Biting the ingredient reveals Essences directly (depth varies —
                  see Section 2).
    Reference:    The Doctrine of Essences, recipe scrolls, an apothecary's guidance,
                  or any other in-world knowledge source.
    Prior use:    They have brewed with this ingredient before and learned from it.

  If the player does NOT know an ingredient's Essences and has no reference:
    They may Rawcraft it first (see Section 2).
    If they brew without knowing, they are brewing blind — they will get a result,
    but you adjudicate the Essences present and do not tell them in advance.
    Primary Negations they didn't know about still collapse the brew. This is how
    early alchemists died. It is also how they learned.

Step 2 — Identify All Essences
  List every Essence from every ingredient, noting tier (Primary/Secondary/Tertiary).
  If a player doesn't know an ingredient's Essences, see Step 1 above.

Step 3 — Check All Ingredient Pairs for Opposition
  For N ingredients, there are N*(N-1)/2 pairs to check.
  Check each pair against the five Opposition pairs (see Section 3).
  Classify each active Opposition by negation tier.

  PRIMARY NEGATION: Both opposing Essences are Primary in their ingredients.
    Result: The entire brew collapses. No product. All ingredients wasted.
    This is a hard stop. It does not matter what other Essences are in the brew.

  SECONDARY NEGATION: One or both opposing Essences are Secondary.
    Result: The brew works. Those specific Essences are significantly weakened
    in the final compound. All other Essences express normally.

  TERTIARY NEGATION: One or both opposing Essences are Tertiary.
    Result: The brew works. Minor weakening on those Essences. Treat as flavor.
    Not worth significant mechanical consequence.

Step 4 — Determine the Compound's Effects
  Every Essence that has not been Primary-Negated expresses in the final product.
  Secondary-Negated Essences still express, but at significantly reduced potency.
  Total effects = all unique non-negated Essences across all ingredients.
  Match each Essence to the appropriate consumable effect from the Gear Doc (Section 5).

Step 5 — Determine Base Quality
  Without any tools: Standard
  With a Retort:     Potent (no roll needed to reach this)

Step 6 — Potency Roll (Player's Choice, Optional)
  The player rolls 1d20 against their Guile Target Number.

  Roll 1 (Critical):    Exceptional
  Roll under Guile:     Potent
                        (Expert tier: this result is Exceptional instead)
  Roll over Guile:      Standard (no improvement, no loss — still works)
  Roll 20 (Crit Fail):  Tainted

  TAINTED: The compound still functions at Standard quality. However, one unintended
  secondary Essence from any ingredient in the brew also expresses. You choose which
  secondary Essence activates — pick whichever creates the most interesting situation,
  not necessarily the most punishing one. The compound is not ruined. It just also does
  something extra.

  If using an Alembic: A roll of 20 becomes Standard instead of Tainted.
  If using a Calcinator: Roll twice, take the lower result (Advantage).


CONCENTRATION: RANKING ESSENCES ACROSS MULTIPLE INGREDIENTS
  Copy-count sets rank. When a brew uses more than one unit of a given ingredient, the
  number of copies determines how that ingredient's Essences weigh against the rest of the
  pot -- more copies of an ingredient pull its Essences toward the FOREFRONT of the final
  compound; fewer copies leave them further back.

  Example: a 3-ingredient hierarchy where Ingredient A leads, B is secondary, C is
  tertiary -- brew 3 units of A, 2 of B, 1 of C. The ratio of copies is the sculpting tool
  a master uses to force a precise hierarchy instead of letting everything the pot express
  land flat and undifferentiated.

  This does not replace the Law of Affinity -- it sharpens it. Affinity already says shared
  Essences amplify each other; concentration is the dial that lets a brewer deliberately
  choose WHICH Essence dominates the final expression when a brew draws on many ingredients
  at once, rather than leaving the balance to chance. GM adjudication, not rigid math: weigh
  the copy-ratios, then rule on which Essences land as the compound's effective
  Primary/Secondary/Tertiary in play, same spirit as every other ruling in this document.


TOOL MODIFIER STACKING (FULL REFERENCE)
  No tools:              Base Standard. Potency roll may improve.
  Mortar & Pestle only:  Same as above. Required to brew at all. Without it, only
                         Rawcraft is available.
  + Retort:              Base becomes Potent without a roll.
  + Calcinator:          Potency roll made with Advantage.
  + Alembic:             Roll of 20 becomes Standard, not Tainted.
  All four tools:        Start at Potent, roll with Advantage, protected from Taint.


QUALITY TIERS AND HP/FP VALUES (SOURCED FROM GEAR DOC)

  Healing compounds scale as follows across the existing potion ladder:
    Standard:    4 HP    (matches: Potion of Minor Healing)
    Potent:      8 HP    (matches: Potion of Healing)
    Exceptional: 12 HP   (matches: Potion of Plentiful Healing)

  Magicka compounds scale identically (same ladder exists in Gear Doc):
    Standard:    4 FP    (matches: Potion of Minor Magicka)
    Potent:      8 FP    (matches: Potion of Magicka)
    Exceptional: 12 FP   (matches: Potion of Plentiful Magicka)

  Enhancement potions (Fortify, Resist, etc.) are binary in the Gear Doc —
  they either work or they don't. Quality tier affects duration or magnitude
  for these effects:
    Standard:    The listed effect, normal duration (3 rounds per Gear Doc).
    Potent:      The listed effect, doubled duration (6 rounds).
    Exceptional: The listed effect, doubled magnitude AND doubled duration.
                 (e.g., Resist Fire: half damage -> immune to one hit of fire,
                 then half; or +4 bonus instead of +2 for Fortify potions)

  Poisons scale in damage dealt:
    Standard:    Listed Gear Doc value (Weak Poison: 2 damage on hit)
    Potent:      Doubled value (4 damage on hit)
    Exceptional: Tripled value (6 damage on hit) or enhanced secondary effect


