SECTION 8: FOUR WORKED EXAMPLES FOR REFERENCE

EXAMPLE 1: THE BASIC HEALING POTION
  Ingredients: Blue Mountain Flower + Wheat
  Blue Mountain Flower: VITALIS[P], CAECITAS[S]
  Wheat: VITALIS[P], FORTITAS[S]
  Pairs to check: 1 pair (Blue Mountain Flower vs Wheat)
  Opposition check: CAECITAS vs FORTITAS — not an opposing pair. VITALIS vs VITALIS —
  same Essence, not an opposition. No negation.
  Essences expressed: VITALIS (amplified via Affinity), CAECITAS (secondary, minor),
  FORTITAS (secondary, minor)
  Primary effect: VITALIS amplified — Healing compound.
  Secondary effects: trace CAECITAS and FORTITAS — the healed character feels briefly
  more resilient and their outline is slightly harder to see for a moment. These are
  flavor only at secondary-secondary concentration.
  Result: Potion of Minor Healing.
  Quality: Standard (4 HP). Potent with successful Guile roll (8 HP).

EXAMPLE 2: THE POISON BLADE
  Intent: Apply VENITAS to a weapon for the next hit.
  Ingredients: Deathbell + Skeever Tail
  Deathbell: VENITAS[P], GRAVITAS[S]
  Skeever Tail: VENITAS[P], AGILITAS[T]
  Pairs to check: 1 pair
  Opposition check: GRAVITAS vs AGILITAS — they ARE an opposing pair.
  GRAVITAS[S] vs AGILITAS[T] — TERTIARY NEGATION. Flavor only. Both slightly weakened.
  Other check: VENITAS vs VENITAS — same Essence, amplified.
  Essences expressed: VENITAS (amplified), GRAVITAS (slightly weakened secondary),
  AGILITAS (slightly weakened tertiary)
  Primary effect: Poison damage on hit (Weak Poison: 2 damage, or 4 at Potent).
  Secondary: A very slight slowing sensation — flavor only at this concentration.
  Result: Poison compound. Applied to a weapon as per Gear Doc.
  Quality: Standard (2 damage next hit). Potent (4 damage next hit).

EXAMPLE 3: FIRE RESISTANCE (3 ingredients)
  Intent: A compound that makes the drinker resistant to fire damage.
  Ingredients: Snowberries + Fire Salts + Nordic Barnacle
  Snowberries: FORTITAS[P], GLACIES[S], FULGUR[T]
  Fire Salts: IGNIS[P], FORTITAS[S]
  Nordic Barnacle: FORTITAS[P], VITALIS[S]
  Pairs to check: 3 pairs
  Pair 1 — Snowberries vs Fire Salts:
    FORTITAS[P] vs IGNIS[P] — not an opposing pair. No negation.
    GLACIES[S] vs IGNIS[P] — THEY ARE an opposing pair. GLACIES[S] vs IGNIS[P]:
    one is Secondary, one is Primary — SECONDARY NEGATION. Both significantly weakened.
    The GLACIES and IGNIS cancel each other substantially.
    FULGUR[T] vs FORTITAS[S] — not an opposing pair. No negation.
  Pair 2 — Snowberries vs Nordic Barnacle:
    FORTITAS[P] vs FORTITAS[P] — same Essence, amplified.
    GLACIES[S] vs VITALIS[S] — not an opposing pair. No negation.
    FULGUR[T] vs FORTITAS[P] — not an opposing pair. No negation.
  Pair 3 — Fire Salts vs Nordic Barnacle:
    IGNIS[P] vs FORTITAS[P] — not an opposing pair.
    FORTITAS[S] vs FORTITAS[P] — same Essence, Affinity applies (additional amplification).
    IGNIS[P] vs VITALIS[S] — not an opposing pair.
  Essences expressed:
    FORTITAS: triple-sourced (Snowberries[P] + Fire Salts[S] + Nordic Barnacle[P])
              — very strong amplification.
    IGNIS: significantly weakened (Secondary Negation with GLACIES).
    GLACIES: significantly weakened (Secondary Negation with IGNIS).
    VITALIS: secondary from Nordic Barnacle — minor healing note.
    FULGUR: tertiary from Snowberries — negligible.
  Primary effect: FORTITAS amplified + IGNIS present (significantly weakened) =
  fire resistance compound. The strong FORTITAS combined with the weakened IGNIS
  produces resistance rather than offense. The healing note from VITALIS is a
  pleasant secondary effect — the drinker also heals 1-2 HP as a flavor effect.
  Result: Potion of Resist Fire (half fire damage, 3 rounds Standard, 6 rounds Potent).
  GM NOTE: The mutual cancellation of IGNIS and GLACIES is working exactly as intended.
  The player has accidentally produced a cleaner compound than they might have if the
  elemental Essences had been stronger.

EXAMPLE 4: THE DISASTROUS BREW (teaching the Primary Negation rule)
  A Novice player finds Imp Stool and Blue Mountain Flower. Both feel warm in the mouth
  via Rawcraft. They decide to combine them for a "super healing potion."
  Ingredients: Blue Mountain Flower + Imp Stool
  Blue Mountain Flower: VITALIS[P], CAECITAS[S]
  Imp Stool: VENITAS[P], VITALIS[S], GRAVITAS[T]
  Pairs to check: 1 pair
  Opposition check: VITALIS[P] (Blue Mountain Flower) vs VENITAS[P] (Imp Stool) —
  PRIMARY NEGATION. Entire brew collapses.
  Result: Nothing. The compound destabilizes. Ingredients wasted. The mortar smells
  faintly of spoiled flowers and something vaguely unpleasant.
  GM NARRATION CUE: "As the paste forms, you notice it beginning to separate — the
  blue color of the flower and the brown of the mushroom refuse to integrate. The
  mixture turns a muddy, unremarkable grey and the smell goes off. You have nothing.
  You know, now, that those two ingredients have something fundamental working against
  each other." The player has just learned the Law of Opposition empirically.
  This is exactly how early alchemists learned it. Welcome to the tradition.


