SECTION 9: GM RULINGS FOR EDGE CASES

WHAT HAPPENS IF THE PLAYER HAS NO MORTAR AND PESTLE?
  Only Rawcraft is available. They can bite an ingredient for a brief, weak primary
  Essence effect. That is all. They cannot brew.

WHAT IF THEY WANT TO USE JUST ONE INGREDIENT?
  One-ingredient compounds are valid. Any character can do this.
  The compound expresses the ingredient's Primary Essence only (no combination needed).
  No Opposition to check. Secondary Essences do not express in a single-ingredient brew —
  there is nothing to combine with, so only the dominant property is released.
  If a player wants to attempt to coax a secondary Essence from a single ingredient
  without a combining agent, call for a Hard Guile roll. This is non-standard technique
  and unreliable. Not something most practitioners would attempt.

WHAT IF A PLAYER ASKS ABOUT COMBINING FOOD/NON-STANDARD ITEMS?
  Anything organic has at least a trace Essence. Apply the "what does it do?" principle.
  Cooked food has had its Essence partially released and is much weaker than raw
  ingredients. A sweetroll does not make an alchemical compound. A raw giant mushroom
  probably has a VITALIS or ANIMA expression worth adjudicating.

CAN A PLAYER MAKE A PARALYSIS COMPOUND?
  Paralysis Poison exists in the Gear Doc. In Essence terms, this is AGILITAS at
  extreme high concentration overwhelming the target's nervous system.
  This requires: AGILITAS[P] from at least two sources, or three+ AGILITAS ingredients.
  Any character who knows the recipe can attempt it — there is no tier gate.
  Standard quality = target makes a Might roll or Paralyzed (next turn lost).
  Potent quality = Paralysis without a saving roll.

CAN POTIONS BE COMBINED IN SEQUENCE?
  Yes. A player can drink a healing potion and then a fortify potion on separate turns.
  Multiple potions of the same type do not stack their primary effect (two Minor Healing
  potions restores 4 HP, not 8 HP — diminishing returns apply). Different effects stack
  normally. The GM may rule that extremely similar effects (two different healing potions)
  produce a diminished second dose if they want to discourage stacking.

CAN A PLAYER COAT A WEAPON WITH A HEALING POTION?
  No. VITALIS expressed as a healing compound requires ingestion. The Essence is not
  delivered effectively through a wound (the body does not absorb it the same way).
  VENITAS on a wound works because it is already doing what it wants to do — damage.
  VITALIS needs to enter through the digestive system to properly engage with the body's
  restorative systems. This is in the lore and is the right answer.

CAN A POISON BE ADMINISTERED VIA FOOD OR DRINK INSTEAD OF A WEAPON?
  Yes -- this is a DELIVERY METHOD, not a new poison type. A tabletop poisoner isn't limited
  to a video game's on-hit-in-combat trigger; slipping something into a meal or a cup is the
  more common real use at the table, and it needs its own rule rather than forcing every
  poison through the weapon-hit mechanic.
  UNDETECTABLE BY TASTE at Standard quality. A suspicious target may get a Guile roll to
  notice something's off, GM's call on when that's warranted.
  DELAY: it does not trigger on ingestion. It takes hold on a timer the GM sets to fit the
  scene -- an hour, the end of a meal, the start of the next scene -- because the entire
  point of this delivery method is being somewhere else when it happens.
  EFFECT IS SITUATIONAL -- it depends entirely on what the alchemist actually brewed, per
  Section 5's normal Essence-to-Effect mapping, same as any other poison. A pure VENITAS
  brew (Nightshade alone, say) still deals its listed damage (Standard 2, Potent 4,
  Exceptional 6) when the delay ends -- the delivery method changes WHEN it triggers, not
  WHAT it does. A GRAVITAS-paired poison still also slows once it lands. Nothing about the
  underlying Essence math changes; only the trigger timing does.
  LINGERING VARIANT (GM's call, situational per recipe): a brew built from multiple VENITAS
  sources, or one the GM judges should hit harder over time rather than in one lump, may
  instead deal its damage across several rounds once triggered rather than as a single hit.
  This is a judgment call per-recipe, not a universal rule -- match the delivery to the
  poison actually built, the same way Concentration lets a brewer choose which Essence leads.


